# Structured data (JSON-LD)

Structured data does not change how a page looks, but it makes your entities unambiguous to search engines and AI systems, and it unlocks rich results. Adoption is still low, which makes it high-leverage. Render it **server-side** so it is in the initial HTML.

## Implementation rules
- Emit JSON-LD as a `<script type="application/ld+json">` inside a Server Component, via `dangerouslySetInnerHTML`.
- **Escape `<` to prevent XSS**: `JSON.stringify(data).replace(/</g, '\\u003c')`, especially where any field could contain user or CMS content.
- Use **absolute URLs** for every `url`, `@id`, `image`, and `logo`. Relative URLs are invalid in JSON-LD.
- Give entities stable `@id` values (e.g. `https://domain.com/#organization`) and reference them across schemas so Organization, WebSite, Article author, and publisher all resolve to the same nodes. Nested, connected entities beat isolated blobs.
- Validate every type against Google's Rich Results Test **and** the Schema.org validator before shipping.
- Only mark up content that is actually visible on the page. Never mark up content that is not present.

## Required site-wide schema (root layout = the "organization details in the header")
Put these in `app/layout.tsx` so every page carries them:
- **Organization**: `name`, `url`, `logo` (ImageObject, absolute), `sameAs` (social/authority profiles), `contactPoint`. Use `LocalBusiness` (or a subtype) instead if the business is location-based, adding `address`, `geo`, `openingHours`.
- **WebSite**: `name`, `url`, and a `potentialAction` SearchAction if the site has internal search (drives the sitelinks search box).

## Per-page-type schema
- **Blog / article pages**: `BlogPosting` or `Article`, with `headline`, `image`, `datePublished`, `dateModified`, `author` as a linked `Person` entity (not a bare string), `publisher` referencing the Organization node, and `mainEntityOfPage`. Author-as-entity and accurate dates are strong trust signals for both rich results and AI citation.
- **Product pages**: `Product` with `offers` (price, currency, availability), `brand`, and `aggregateRating`/`review` only if real ratings exist.
- **Service pages**: `Service` linked to the provider Organization.
- **FAQ blocks**: `FAQPage`. Note: Google narrowed FAQ *rich results in the SERP* to a small set of sites in late 2025, so do not expect the old star-visual, but the markup still helps machine comprehension and AI answers. Only use it for genuine Q&A actually on the page.
- **Breadcrumbs**: `BreadcrumbList` on every nested page.

## Do not
Do not invent AI-specific schema or add schema purely "for AI Overviews". Google has stated no special schema is needed for its generative features. Schema earns its place through rich-result eligibility and entity clarity, nothing more.
